  "opinion": "As an immigrant who spent years adapting to a new country and later became a retired educator in my community, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can shape people's experiences. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just an academic concept—it's the quiet anxiety that comes when someone feels their group's performance is judged by others. For instance, when I watched my grandchildren struggle with math problems, their fear of being labeled 'not a math person' made them hesitant to ask questions. This is especially true for girls and minorities in STEM fields, where the pressure to conform to expectations can overshadow their actual abilities. I believe we must address this issue not through rigid policies but through gentle, community-based approaches. In my time volunteering with local schools, I've learned that building trust and encouraging open dialogue helps students feel safe to explore without fear of judgment. It's crucial to create environments where everyone knows their worth isn't tied to a single subject or test. We should focus on celebrating individual strengths and fostering a sense of belonging rather than trying to fix systemic issues overnight. After all, as a man who grew up in a family with strong academic values but also faced challenges as an immigrant, I understand that change happens slowly and through personal connections. The key is to make sure every child feels they belong in the classroom, not just because they're good at math, but because they're human.",
